gs:my-0 prose-headings:font-700 prose-headings:text-charcoal prose-h1:mb-[32px] prose-h1:mt-[48px] prose-h1:text-[34px] prose-h1:leading-[40px] prose-h1:tracking-[0.25px] md:prose-h1:text-[48px] md:prose-h1:leading-[56px] md:prose-h1:tracking-[0px] lg:prose-h1:text-[60px] lg:prose-h1:leading-[72px] prose-h2:text-[24px] prose-h2:leading-[32px] prose-h2:tracking-[0px] prose-h2:mt-[48px] prose-h2:mb-[24px] md:prose-h2:text-[34px] md:prose-h2:leading-[40px] md:prose-h2:tracking-[0.25px] lg:prose-h2:text-[40px] lg:prose-h2:leading-[48px] lg:prose-h2:tracking-[0px] prose-h3:text-[20px] prose-h3:leading-[32px] prose-h3:tracking-[0.15px] prose-h3:mb-[20px] md:prose-h3:text-[24px] md:prose-h3:leading-[32px] md:prose-h3:tracking-[0px] prose-p:m-0 prose-p:font-500 prose-p:text-charcoal prose-p:text-[14px] prose-p:leading-[24px] prose-p:tracking-[0.1px] prose-p:mb-[20px] md:prose-p:text-[16px] md:prose-p:leading-[32px] md:prose-p:tracking-[0.15px] prose-a:text-blue prose-strong:font-700 prose-blockquote:border-none prose-blockquote:relative prose-p:before:content-[] prose-blockquote:not-italic prose-blockquote:m-0 prose-blockquote:p-[8px_0px_8px_16px] md:prose-blockquote:p-[8px_0px_8px_26px] prose-blockquote:before:absolute prose-blockquote:before:inset-0 prose-blockquote:before:w-[4px] prose-blockquote:before:bg-blue prose-blockquote:before:rounded-full prose-blockquote:before:left-0 md:prose-blockquote:before:w-[6px] prose-ol:pl-[16px] prose-ol:mb-[20px] prose-ol:list-decimal md:prose-ol:pl-[26px] prose-li:marker:proportional-nums prose-ul:pl-[16px] prose-ul:mb-[20px] prose-ul:list-disc md:prose-ul:pl-[26px] prose-li:font-500 prose-li:text-charcoal prose-li:text-[16px] prose-li:leading-[32px] prose-li:m-0 prose-li:p-0 prose-table:table-fixed prose-table:border-[0px] prose-table:text-charcoal prose-table:text-[14px] prose-table:leading-[24px] md:prose-table:text-[16px] prose-tr:grid prose-tr:divide-y-[3px] prose-tr:divide-lavender prose-tr:border-[0px] sm:prose-tr:border-[3px] sm:prose-tr:border-lavender sm:prose-tr:table-row prose-td:p-[32px] sm:prose-td:border-[3px] sm:prose-td:border-lavender prose-th:p-[32px] empty:prose-th:hidden sm:empty:prose-th:table-cell sm:prose-th:border-[3px] sm:prose-th:border-lavender prose-thead:border-[3px] prose-thead:border-lavender prose-tbody:border-[3px] prose-tbody:border-lavender prose-tbody:divide-y-[3px] prose-tbody:divide-lavender"><h2 id="jobdescriptiontemplatefivestepstosuccess">Job Description Template: Five Steps To Success</h2>
<h2 id="concisejobtitle">Concise job title</h2>
<p>The job title should be specific, descriptive, and brief. An example of a good job title is &quot;Marketing Intern.&quot; Bad titles include Marketing Manager or Administrative Assistant. Due to the wide variety of roles in any company, it's important to make sure your position description accurately reflects what employees will actually do on a day-to-day basis. This makes it easier for hiring managers or team leaders to understand if they have the appropriate skill set necessary for that particular job!</p>
<h2 id="anattentiongrabbingfirstparagraph">An Attention-Grabbing First Paragraph</h2>
<p>Once you've drawn in the right candidate with your title, the next step is to keep them engaged by drawing their attention. The first paragraph of a job description will immediately let candidates know if they're qualified for the role or not, so it's important to make sure this section packs a punch! An effective opening sentence should explain what kind of person would be right for the position and why they need these skills. It also needs to mention any requirements such as years of experience, educational background, etc., that potential employees might have. This way, people who don't fit into every requirement can still find jobs that are suitable for their skill sets!</p>
<h2 id="completeandaccuratejobdescription">Complete And Accurate Job Description</h2>
<p>The written job description should be as detailed as possible. Don't leave out any information that might help a candidate decide if they're interested in applying to your company like job duties and job responsibilities! In addition, make sure you include the skills necessary for the role and what kinds of tasks team members will perform on a daily basis. It's also important to highlight how this role contributes to larger goals within the company, so potential hires know their work has purpose and meaning!</p>
<h2 id="realisticjobrequirements">Realistic Job Requirements</h2>
<p>Job requirements should not be too strict. It's good practice to list any qualifications necessary for the role and allow some flexibility so people who don't perfectly match all your expectations can apply! Avoid listing unnecessary or non-essential skills as well. For example: &quot;Must speak fluent French.&quot; This skill isn't really required if you're hiring someone strictly for an administrative assistant position.</p>
<h2 id="providingasenseofthecompanyculture">Providing A Sense Of The Company Culture</h2>
<p>If the job description accurately represents your company, it should give candidates a sense of the work environment. This can help team members feel welcome and motivated to work hard from day one! You don't need to go into too much detail about how employees are rewarded or recognized by management. Instead, focus on providing them with some idea as to how this role fits into the bigger picture so they understand why their efforts matter.</p>
